WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standard reference for JPEG XS (ISO/IEC 21122), a visually
lossless, low-latency, low-complexity image and video coding system. It
defines the core coding algorithm, the rate-distortion model, the latency
budget, and the transport over RTP and SMPTE ST 2110. JPEG XS achieves
compression ratios up to 32:1 with sub-millisecond latency, making it
suitable for real-time IP video transport and virtual production.

WHY IT EXISTS
Traditional codecs like HEVC introduce latency unacceptable for live
production and virtual reality. JPEG XS fills this gap by providing
visually lossless compression with latency below 1 ms. It is the
mandated codec for SMPTE ST 2110-22 transport and is adopted by the
JPEG Committee, intoPIX, and Fraunhofer. GIOP integrates it as the
reference low-latency codec for real-time imaging pipelines.

HOW IT WORKS
JPEG XS uses a line-based discrete wavelet transform (DWT) with 5/3
filter banks, followed by a lightweight entropy coder. The algorithm
processes only a few lines at a time, achieving sub-millisecond latency.

1. Wavelet Transform:
   The input image is decomposed into sub-bands using a 5/3 Le Gall
   wavelet. The forward transform for a 1D signal:
     y[2n] = x[2n] - floor((x[2n-1] + x[2n+1] + 2) / 4)
     y[2n+1] = x[2n+1] + floor((y[2n] + y[2n+2]) / 2)

2. Quantisation:
   Each sub-band is quantised with a uniform dead-zone quantiser:
     q = sign(c) * floor(|c| / delta)
   where delta is the step size determined by the quality parameter.

3. Rate Control:
   The encoder adjusts delta to meet a target bitrate R_target:
     R_target = (pixel_rate * bit_depth * components) / compression_ratio
   For 4K 60p 4:4:4 10-bit, uncompressed rate = 3840*2160*60*3*10 = 14.93 Gbps.
   At 32:1 compression, R_target ≈ 467 Mbps.

4. Latency Budget:
   T_total = T_input + T_encode + T_transport + T_decode + T_output
   T_encode + T_decode < 32 lines (typically < 0.5 ms at 4K).

5. RTP Payload (IETF RFC 9134):
   The codestream is packetised into RTP packets. Each packet carries a
   slice of the image, enabling line-sequential decoding.

